📘 𝐃𝐚𝐲 𝟏𝟐 – 𝐋𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐧 𝐆𝐞𝐫𝐦𝐚𝐧 𝐀𝟏 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐌𝐞: 𝐆𝐞𝐫𝐦𝐚𝐧 𝐕𝐞𝐫𝐛𝐬 & 𝐒𝐭𝐫𝐮𝐜𝐭𝐮𝐫𝐞 Today, let’s dive into the fascinating world of German verbs! Understanding them is key to building strong sentences.



✅ 𝐖𝐡𝐚𝐭 𝐢𝐬 𝐚 𝐕𝐞𝐫𝐛? 

A verb describes an action. In German, the structure of a sentence heavily depends on the verb. 👉 Ich spiele Fußball. (I play football.)



⚙️ 𝐕𝐞𝐫𝐛 𝐒𝐭𝐫𝐮𝐜𝐭𝐮𝐫𝐞 (Verbstruktur): German verbs have a "Verb stamm" (stem of verb) and an "Endung" (ending, typically -en or -n). 👉 Example: lern + en = lernen (to learn)



📚 𝐂𝐨𝐦𝐦𝐨𝐧 𝐆𝐞𝐫𝐦𝐚𝐧 𝐕𝐞𝐫𝐛𝐬:

heißen (to be called)

kommen (to come)

wohnen (to live)

machen (to do)

hören (to hear)

sprechen (to speak)



🔄 𝐕𝐞𝐫𝐛 𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐣𝐮𝐠𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 (Verbkonjugation): Verbs change their endings based on the subject. 👉 Ich komme aus China. (I come from China.) 👉 Kommt ihr aus Japan? (Do you come from Japan?)



⚖️ 𝐑𝐞𝐠𝐮𝐥𝐚𝐫 𝐯𝐬. 𝐈𝐫𝐫𝐞𝐠𝐮𝐥𝐚𝐫 𝐕𝐞𝐫𝐛𝐬:

▶️ 𝐑𝐞𝐠𝐞𝐥𝐦äß𝐢𝐠𝐞 𝐕𝐞𝐫𝐛𝐞𝐧 (Regular verbs) Also known as "schwache Verben" (weak verbs). The verb stem doesn't change. 👉 lernen → du lernst

▶️ 𝐔𝐧𝐫𝐞𝐠𝐞𝐥𝐦äß𝐢𝐠𝐞 𝐕𝐞𝐫𝐛𝐞𝐧 (Irregular verbs) Also known as "starke Verben" (strong verbs). The verb stem changes in certain cases. 👉 sprechen → du sprichst



✍️ 𝐏𝐫𝐚𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐜𝐞 𝐓𝐢𝐩: Pick a regular and an irregular verb from the list above. Try to conjugate them with "Ich" and "Du". 

For example: 

📌 Regular: Ich wohne in Berlin. / Du wohnst in Paris. 

📌 Irregular: Ich esse Pizza. / Du isst Brot.



